ow that Dysnomia has to be relatively\nmassive (mass ratio of q = 0.01--0.03) and large (radius of $R_s$ $\\geq$ 300\nkm) to slow down Eris to synchronized rotation. These simulations also indicate\nthat -- assuming tidal parameters usually considered for transneptunian objects\n-- the density of Dysnomia should be 1.8-2.4 $g cm^{-3}$, an exceptionally high\nvalue among similarly sized transneptunian objects, putting important\nconstraints on the formation conditions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 15 Nov 2022 08:52:51 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 25 Nov 2022 06:50:19 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-01-04"}
